## Strategic orientations

Facing the COVID-19 pandemic and its variants' waves since 2020, the world is still adapting to a new paradigm made of strong volatility and uncertainty:

- /uni25A0 Macroeconomic and geopolitical environments: (i)/uni00A0recovery at a heterogeneous pace between developed economies who have already recovered or are about to recover to pre-COVID-19 growth levels and developing economies that in majority will not have fully caught with pre-COVID-19 output levels by 2022, (ii)/uni00A0expectations to see Chinese economy slowing down and knock-on e/ff ects on global economy growth outlook and supply chains, (iii)/uni00A0rising inflation and uncertainty on interest rates and (iv)/uni00A0increasing geopolitical tensions between blocks, threatening global stability and growth;
- /uni25A0 Increasing pressure on the insurance industry: (i)/uni00A0increasing complexity and cost of regulation ( e.g. , IFRS/uni00A017 ( 1 ) , OECD global agreement on corporate taxation, SFDR (2) , CSRD (3) , GDPR /uni00A0 (4) , etc.) doubled with State interventionism, especially for European players ( e.g. , restrictions on foreign cloud providers), (ii)/uni00A0higher frequency and severity of emerging risks ( e.g. , natural catastrophes, cyber risks), and (iii)/uni00A0price pressure and claims costs inflation in Property & Casualty;
- /uni25A0 Growth opportunities: (i)/uni00A0demand for Health insurance is still rising, (ii)/uni00A0new insurance needs triggered by increase in risks variety and continued evolution of global GDP's main growth drivers towards more digital, services and 'asset-light' industries ( e.g. , climate change, energy transition, cyber security), (iii)/uni00A0good momentum in Life & Savings to deploy innovative products and optimize legacy books, and (iv)/uni00A0tech & data more and more critical to bring value-for-money services to customers, di/ff erentiate from peers and optimize operations.

